window.docContents[28].resolve({"/Lecture-1___-Motivation-and-Propositional-Logic/First-Proofs-in-Lean/#Formal-Software-Verification--Lecture-1___-Motivation-and-Propositional-Logic--First-Proofs-in-Lean--Negation":{"contents":"In Lean, ¬P is defined as P → False, where False is the proposition with no proof. A proof of ¬P is a function that turns any proof of P into a proof of False.\n\nexample (P : Prop) (hP : P) (hnP : ¬P) : False := hnP hP\n\n\nEvery tactic for implication therefore works for negation. The contrapositive direction below needs only intro and application.\n\ntheorem contrapositive (P Q : Prop) (hPQ : P → Q) :\n    ¬Q → ¬P := by\n  intro hnQ hP\n  exact hnQ (hPQ hP)\n\n\nIntroducing double negation is equally direct.\n\nexample (P : Prop) (hP : P) : ¬¬P := fun hnP => hnP hP\n\n\nThe second De Morgan law combines the rules seen so far. The tactic constructor also introduces a biconditional, splitting it into the two implications.\n\ntheorem deMorgan_or (P Q : Prop) : ¬(P ∨ Q) ↔ ¬P ∧ ¬Q := by\n  constructor\n  · intro h\n    constructor\n    · intro hP\n      exact h (Or.inl hP)\n    · intro hQ\n      exact h (Or.inr hQ)\n  · intro h hPQ\n    cases hPQ with\n    | inl hP => exact h.left hP\n    | inr hQ => exact h.right hQ\n\n\n","context":"Formal Software Verification\u0009Lecture 1: Motivation and Propositional Logic\u0009First Proofs in Lean","header":"1.5.4. Negation","id":"/Lecture-1___-Motivation-and-Propositional-Logic/First-Proofs-in-Lean/#Formal-Software-Verification--Lecture-1___-Motivation-and-Propositional-Logic--First-Proofs-in-Lean--Negation"}});